PROBLEM

In a structural laboratory one of the students has found the structure of a PROBLEM protein, modelled by a previous post-doc.  However, it seems it is incomplete.  
According to the experimental data,  this protein works forms a homodimer complex when it's activated. But it's unclear the function and if it works at all.
Try to answer the following questions:

a) What function do you think it may have? 
b) Does it belongs to some family of PFAM?. If so, obtain the HMM profile from PFAM and name it p28b.hmm
c) Does the structure of this protein belongs to some fold in SCOP?, which one?
d) Obtain the secondary structure of the problem with DSSP and name it p28d.dssp (WARNING NOTE: DSSP requieres the full MAINCHAIN, with only CA trace it will not work). Name the structure of the monomer with all atoms p28d.pdb
e) Do you think the prediction of secondary structure agrees with the actual secondary structure from DSSP?. Obtain an alignment as proof and name it p28e.aln. Is this prediction reliable? 
f) Do you think the structure is correct? Can you prove it? show an image of the energies that prove it and name it p28f.png
g) Find if there is some structural problem and show the location of all those you find with an image (name it p28g.png). What's(are) the sequence fragment(s) with this problem?
h) Do you think the protein PROBLEM, as it is originally in the file, can work as a dimer? show an image that can prove it (name it p28h.png)
i) Even if it was a monomer, do you think it will work with the function you selected in answer "a"? Use a sequence alignment (ie. you can use the sequence of 3 homologs) to show the conservation/non-conservation of functional residues. Name the alignment p28i.aln 
   Mark the functionally important amino-acids (conserved or non-conserved) in the alignment with the symbol # at the bottom.
j) To further proof your answer in "i": Show an image of the structure of the active site with the relevant aminoacids that preserve (or don't preserve) the function in its active form (i.e. if it requires a cofactor, such as ATP, Ca+2,  etc. include it (or an agonist/antagonist) in the active site interacting with the corresponding residues of the PROBLEM). Name it p28j.png and the pdb as p28j.pdb
k) If the structure of the PROBLEM was incorrect (answer in g), try to fix it. Name the new monomer model as p28k.pdb. Compare the energies with PROSA (show the result with an image and name it p28k.png)
l) Do you think your new model can work as a dimer? If so, obtain the structure of the dimer and name it p28l.pdb. Show with an image if the original model couldn't make a dimer, why your new model can (or cannot) make it?. Name the image p28l.png

